	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />I find developing games more rewarding than developing emulators. A game, no matter how simple, always presents something new. But emulators usually just allow people to play the same old games everyone already knows without offering anything new.
<br />
<br />Given the fact that there are already a couple of great emulators that do almost everything anyone would ever need, I don't see a point in making yet another emulator unless there is something innovative about it, like a (preferably useful) feature that was never implemented before.
<br />
<br />I can understand people that code emulators as a form of studying the system (even though I think they'd be making better use of their time if they were coding games instead), but such emulators rarely offer anything interesting (as opposed to games), and should probably be kept private.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


